<p style="line-height:24px;"><span style="font-size:48px;line-height:12px;">I</span> can&#8217;t be the only one feeling short of time lately. We all are so busy. I feel like I&#8217;m not paying attention to the things that are important to me, or even amusing. The election kept me from getting my garlic and potatoes planted <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.motherearthnews.com/organic-gardening/time-to-plant-garlic-with-growing-tips-zbcz1409">during the waning crescent moon</a> last week. And yesterday, I missed the observation of the latest sunrise of the year, 7:35 a.m., observed by the hardy from the patio of the<a target="_blank"  href="https://www.westword.com/restaurants/lakeview-lounge-has-new-owners-but-no-plans-to-change-11633508"> Lakeview Lounge</a>, overlooking Sloans Lake in Denver. (We all can try again in March, when the sunrise service observes the first day of daylight saving time.)</p>

<p>I have to say that even though I&#8217;m irritated by having to reset my clocks, and am entertained by the <a target="_blank"  href="https://leg.colorado.gov/bills/sb20-105">semi-regular attempts to get Colorado to stop participating</a> in the biannual national ritual, I am glad for the fall back every single year.</p>

<p>I know that the early rosy bliss quickly gives way to the true darkness of winter, but that extra hour of morning daylight just makes it a bit easier to get up and out in the chill air, to take a breath and give thanks for the wonder of living here.</p>

<p>There are so many tales out there to tell and places that make Colorado special. Today, we start the newsletter with a place that our reporter and photographer have literally been waiting years to visit, a long tunnel under a mountain that is the crucial economic artery of the Uncompahgre Valley. And yeah, it&#8217;s dark in there.</p>

