<h2><strong>Going under the mountains to inspect the lifeline of the Uncompahgre Valley</strong></h2>

</mj-text><mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px">&nbsp;<a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/2021/11/07/gunnison-tunnel-irrigates-uncompahgre-valley"><img align="center" width="100%" src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2021/11/110421GunnisonTunnel_008.jpg?w=1200" style="border: 0px; width:100%; max-width:600px; margin: 0px;" /></a></mj-text>
<!-- Cutline -->
<mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px"><p class="cutline">The entrance of the Gunnison Tunnel Thursday November 4, 2021. (William Woody, Special to The Colorado Sun)</p></mj-text><mj-text>

<p>It&#8217;s tempting to think of the water cycle we all studied in school (you know, rain &gt; lakes &amp; rivers &gt; evaporation &gt; rain) when you try to imagine the way that water moves around our state. But after 150 years or so of manipulation, Colorado&#8217;s beautiful mountains, valleys, rivers and streams are essentially just a handful of giant basins to capture and move water â€” complete with plumbing.</p>

<p>For this week&#8217;s cover story, reporter <strong>Jason Blevins</strong> and photographer <strong>William Woody</strong> hitched a ride through an essential part of Colorado&#8217;s plumbing â€” the 112-years-young <strong>Gunnison Tunnel</strong>. It&#8217;s not an exaggeration to say that without this tunnel, the lauded <strong>Uncompahgre Valley</strong> growing region â€” aka the home of Olathe Sweet sweet corn and other iconic produce â€” wouldn&#8217;t exist.</p>

<p>The Gunnison Tunnel moves a <em>lot</em> of water from the <strong>Gunnison River</strong> to the valley every year. But the thing about these pesky human brains we have is that they are really bad at visualizing really, really big numbers. So how do we wrap our minds around a massive, arcane concept like 500,000 acre-feet?</p>

<p>Let&#8217;s start small. Imagine a shipping container (like the ones you see on trains and trucks) full of water. The average single-family household will use a little more than 57 of those containers every year.</p>

</mj-text><mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px">&nbsp;<img align="center" width="100%" src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2021/11/shipping-container-vs-household.jpg?w=1200" style="border: 0px; width:100%; max-width:600px; margin: 0px;" /></a></mj-text><mj-text>

<p>That seems like a lot of water, but last time I checked, we have a lot more than one house in Colorado. <strong>Dillon Reservoir</strong>, one of <strong>Denver Water</strong>&#8217;s largest, can hold enough to serve 128,652 homes for a year.</p>

</mj-text><mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px">&nbsp;<img align="center" width="100%" src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2021/11/dillon-reservoir.jpg?w=1200" style="border: 0px; width:100%; max-width:600px; margin: 0px;" /></a></mj-text><mj-text>

<p>And <em>all of that</em> water adds up to 257,000 acre-feet or so, about half of the amount that moves through the tunnel every year. In fact, the Gunnison Tunnel moves as much water as the entire Front Range pulls from the Colorado River basin every year!</p>

</mj-text><mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px">&nbsp;<img align="center" width="100%" src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2021/11/Dillon-vs-Front-Range-vs-Gunnison.jpg?w=1200" style="border: 0px; width:100%; max-width:600px; margin: 0px;" /></a></mj-text><mj-text>

