</mj-text><mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px">&nbsp;<img align="center" width="100%" src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2021/11/IMG_8262.jpg?w=1200" style="border: 0px; width:100%; max-width:600px; margin: 0px;" /></a></mj-text>
<!-- Cutline -->
<mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px"><p class="cutline">The signature sandwich of Pueblo is a Slopper. The debate is over whether it should be served open faced or closed with a bun before green chile is poured on. (Dana Coffield, The Colorado Sun)</p></mj-text><mj-text>

<p>I have a weirdly large number of Pueblo or Pueblo-adjacent people â€” see: <a target="_blank"  href="http://twitter.com/brofax">Eric</a> â€” in my circle, and they talk enough about the city&#8217;s signature dish, <a target="_blank"  href="https://pueblopulp.com/a-pulp-short-the-pueblo-slopper/">the Slopper</a>, that I assumed I must have eaten it at least once. But until Saturday, I had never once savored a hand-shaped beef patty, grilled and dressed with American cheese, placed on a thick slice of slightly-charred sourdough bread and baptized with a ladle of spicy green chile.</p>

<p>If you read that ingredient list and thought, &#8220;That&#8217;s not a Slopper!!!&#8220; then welcome to the high-stakes world of defining the Slopper. Depending on your chosen level of Slopper orthodoxy, you need a bun, not bread. Or shredded cheese <em>on top</em> of the bun, instead of the burger. Or serve the whole thing open-faced. But no matter which way you order it, make it or serve it, you&#8217;ll find some Steel City religion with your first bite.</p>

<p>When you&#8217;re in town, get the originals at <a target="_blank"  href="https://goo.gl/maps/yMSJMNMw25e1wTCk7"><strong>Gray&#8217;s Coors Tavern</strong></a> or <a target="_blank"  href="https://goo.gl/maps/DcJYjHoaocdBay247"><strong>The Sunset Inn</strong></a>. Or you can use <a target="_blank"  href="https://www.movetotraveling.com/slopper-recipe-based-on-pueblo-slopper/">this recipe</a>, from a resident of Spain who grew up near Pueblo, to make one at home. (And yes, you should use Pueblo green chiles.)</p>

</mj-text><mj-table><tr style="border-bottom:1px solid #fcd232;text-align:right;"><td style="padding:0px;font-size:12px"><strong>â€” Dana</strong></td><td style="padding: 6px 6px;width:24px;"><img style="width:24px;height:24px;border:0px solid #fcd232;border-radius:50%; padding:0;" width="24px" height="24px" align="center" src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2019/07/DANAMUGKS.jpg?resize=424,424" /></td></tr></mj-table><mj-text></p>

