<h2><strong>William Sonn&#8217;s "Something Like Treason" tells a strange but true Colorado-based story of WWII</strong></h2>

</mj-text><mj-text padding="0px 0px 0px 0px">&nbsp;<center><a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/?p=206909"><img align="center" width="100%" src="https://lede-admin.coloradosun.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2021/11/DS_Somethingliketreason-final-bookcover-3.jpeg?w=1200" style="border: 0px; width:100%; max-width:200px; margin: 0px;" /></a></center></mj-text><mj-text>
&nbsp;
<!-- Blockquote -->
<blockquote>&#8220;...The Army never acknowledged that the company was, in essence, a holding pen for undesirables. But the men of the 620th caught on quickly. By now â€¦ even the men who had entered the military anxious to fight for the U.S. were behaving the way the Army perceived them.&#8221;<br /><br /><span class="source">â€” From &#8220;Something Like Treason: Pro-German American Soldiers and the Plot to Bring the War Home&#8221;</span></blockquote>

<p><strong>EXCERPT:</strong> Tales of Camp Hale, home of the 10th Mountain Division, are legion. But this passage from "Something Like Treason" tells the true story of another U.S. Army company, also based at that famous encampment, that was designed as a landing spot for misfits, including men who were alienated, brilliant, suspected of harboring anti-American sentiment â€” or gay. Led by the only American soldier convicted of treason in the U.S. during World War II, they plotted sabotage to disrupt the war effort. Despite sentences ranging from death to long terms in Leavenworth prison, their fates ultimately took a surprising turn.</p>

<p>&gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/?p=206909?pico=clean"><strong>Read the entire SunLit Special Edition excerpt.</strong></a></p>

<p><strong>THE SUNLIT INTERVIEW: </strong>Bill Sonn, an author and long-time writer whose work has appeared in a wide variety of publications, also is a former news and communications executive who served as a consultant to health care companies. While doing some research for a client on hospital development at the History Colorado library, he noticed in the library catalog a reference to court-martial and Camp Hale. Intrigued, he ended up digging through four boxes of material about the 620th Engineer General Service Company â€” launching four years of research on a strange chapter in World War II history. Here&#8217;s a segment from the interview.</p>

<p><strong>Sun: Tell us this book&#8217;s backstory. Not much has been written about this piece of World War II history.</strong></p>

<p><strong>Sonn:</strong> There&#8217;ve been a few magazine articles, a research paper (written at Metro State University), reams of (mostly adulatory) stuff about Camp Hale, and rarely with any mention of German POWs or would-be traitors at the place. A thin book about one of the plot leaders came out a couple of years ago. None measured up to a three-part New Yorker series in 1950 about the same guy written by the excellent E.J. Kahn, Jr.</p>

<p>I ended up telling a longer story about these misfits. Understanding them led into tales of Nazi spies and the rise of fascism in the United States, an FBI turf war, the spread of German POW camps around the country, judicial reform, the second Red Scare, racism and, among others, the prosperity and then rusting of America in the post-war era.</p>

<p>&gt;&gt; <a target="_blank"  href="https://coloradosun.com/?p=206954?pico=clean"><strong>Read the entire interview with author William Sonn.</strong></a></p>

